# Git & GitHub workflow

## Relationship to other rules

Coding and project context: **`gpxmapper-core.mdc`**, **`python-standards.mdc`**. This file is **git-only** (commits, branches, PRs) and is the **only** project rule for commit message format (no separate commit-message rule file).

## Commit message rules

- **Subject line (mandatory):** `[<KEY>-<number>] <type>(<scope>): <description>` — the **issue key and number must appear at the start of the first line**, then a space, then conventional `type`, optional `(scope)`, optional `!`, colon, space, and a non-empty description. Examples: `[GPXM-1] fix(cli): handle bad color`, `[GPXM-3] chore(ci): refresh workflow`.
- **Enforcement:** `pre-commit` runs `scripts/check_commit_message.py` on the `commit-msg` stage (after installing hooks: `uv run pre-commit install --hook-type commit-msg`). Exempt first lines: `Merge `, `Revert `, `Pull request`, `fixup!`, `squash!`, `amend!` (prefix match as in the script).
- **Commitizen:** `.cz.toml` sets `allowed_prefixes` to include `[GPXM-` so the Commitizen hook accepts GPXM ticket–prefixed subjects (it skips strict regex for those prefixes); the ticket-key script above still requires the full `[KEY-n] type…` shape for normal commits.
- Determine `<KEY>-<number>` from the branch name when possible (e.g. `GPXM-1-nominatim-…` → `[GPXM-1]`, or `ABC-123` → `[ABC-123]`).
- Scope: the affected module(s); omit only when truly global (`chore: …` with empty scope is allowed if type allows it).
- Types: feat, fix, docs, style, refactor, test, chore, perf, build, ci, bump, revert (see script for the exact allowed set).
- Keep the description concise (under ~50 characters when practical).
- Use imperative mood (e.g., "add" not "added" or "adds").
- Do not end the subject with a period.
- Use lowercase for the first word of the description unless it is a proper noun.
- Put extra context in the **body** after a blank line (optional but encouraged).

## Branch naming conventions

- Use kebab-case (lowercase with hyphens)
- Follow the pattern: `<type>/<issue-number>-<short-description>` or `<issue-number>-<short-description>`
- Types: feature, bugfix, hotfix, release, support
- Example: `feature/123-add-dark-mode`, `PROJECT-123-add-dark-mode`

## Pull request guidelines

- Link related issues using keywords (Fixes #123, Closes #456)
- Provide a clear description of changes
- Add screenshots for UI changes
- Ensure all CI checks pass before requesting review
- Keep PRs focused and small when possible
